data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, `ThreadAbortException`, or `Thread.ResetAbort`. It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which work identically in .NET 8.

**No Thread.Abort migration is needed here.**

That said, the code would benefit from modernization to use `Task`/`Parallel` instead of raw threads:

```csharp
public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
{
    Parallel.ForEach(items, item => Process(item));
}
```

This gives you thread-pool efficiency and simpler cancellation support (via `CancellationToken`) if you need it later.
